Regression analysis

Reading the data into R and exploring it’s structure and dimensions:

## [1] 166   7
## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ gender  : Factor w/ 2 levels "F","M": 1 2 1 2 2 1 2 1 2 1 ...
##  $ Age     : int  53 55 49 53 49 38 50 37 37 42 ...

##  $ deep    : num  3.58 2.92 3.5 3.5 3.67 ...

##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...
##  $ Points  : int  25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26 ...

The data has 166 rows (observations) and 7 columns (variables). One of the variables, gender, is a factor with two levels.Others, including age, attitude, deep, stra, surf and points, are numeric.

Visualizing the data and inspecting summeries of the variables: 

##  gender       Age           attitude          deep            stra

##       surf           Points     
##  Min.   :1.583   Min.   : 7.00

##  3rd Qu.:3.167   3rd Qu.:27.75  
##  Max.   :4.333   Max.   :33.00

The dataset includes much more women (110) than men (56). Age ranges from 17 to 55, with a 25.51 as the mean age, so the age distribution is strongly skewed on left. Scores on the Points variable range from 7 to 33 with a mean of 22.73. Other variables, including attitude (mean=3.14), deep (mean=3.12), stra (mean=3.12) and surf (mean=2.79) range from 1 to 5. There is a somewhat strong correlation between points and attitude (0.44). There is also a correlation between surf and deep (-0.32), although this correlation seemes strong only for men (-0.62) and pretty much nonexistet for women (-0.09). Men also have a correlation between surf and attitude (-0.37), but this does not appear for women (-0.015).

Fitting a regression line and showing the summary:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.1550  -3.4346   0.5156   3.6401  10.8952 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.0171     3.6837   2.991  0.00322 ** 
## attitude      3.3952     0.5741   5.913 1.93e-08 ***
## stra          0.8531     0.5416   1.575  0.11716    
## surf         -0.5861     0.8014  -0.731  0.46563    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.296 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2074, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1927 
## F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.156e-08

The equation could be written like this: y = 11.02 + 3.34(attitude) + 0.85(stra) -0.59(surf), with y being the predicted value of “Points”.Only the variable “attitude” explained changes in “Points” significantly (B=3.4, p < 0.001). The B of 3.4 means that higher attitude predicts higher scores on Points. Intercept of 11.01 means that this is the point where the regression line crosses the y-axis. Stra (B=0.85, p = 0.18) and surf (B=-0.59, p=0.47) weren’t significant predictors, so they will be removed in the next analysis.

Fitting the better model:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

Attitude significantly explains Points (B=3.53, p < 0.001). Higher scores on attitude predict higher scores on Points. Multiple R-squared of 0.19 means that this model explains 19% of all the variaton in the dependent variable (points). This is generally considered a low R-squared value, although if you think about it, if “attitude” single-handedly explains 19 % of all the variation in “Points”, I would say it’s quite a lot!

Producing the diagnostic plots:

From the Residuals vs Fitted -plot we can see that size of the residuals does not depend on the explanatory variable, since there is no pattern to be seen in the scatterplot.QQ-plot is produced to evaluate wheter the residuals are normally distributed.It seems that the residuals fit reasonably well within the line, which means that they seem to fit to the normality assumption. From the Residuals vs Leverage plot we can see that no single value stands out with expectionally high leverage. In conclusion, our model seems to fit the standards!

Logistic regression

Data combines two student alcohol consumption data sets. It includes 35 variables, which measure grades, alcohol use and different background charasteristics.

I choose variables “failures”, “absences”, “sex”, and “age” to predict higher alcohol use. I believe higher failures and higher absences wil be related to higher alcohol use. I believe that male sex and younger age will also predict higher alchol use.

Now, let’s explore the relationships of these variables and high alcohol use numerically and graphically.

Box plot of the relationship between high_use and absences (gender included):

Box plot of the relationship between high_use and age (gender included):

Okay, we can see that male sex, absences and failures are all related to higher alcohol consumption (as predicted). Older age seems to affect differently to men’s and women’s alchohol use and there doesn’t seem to be a straightfoward relationship between age and high use (unlike predicted).

From the summary we can already see that absences and sex are strong predictors for the alcohol consumption with high p-values and failures seems to be significant predictor as well, although with slightly lower p-value (p=0.036). OR for male sex is 2.58 , meaning that men are over two times more likely than women to be in the “high_use”-group. High value for failures increases the likelihood of higher use of alcohol as well (OR = 1.5), as does high value for absences (OR = 1.09). Age however, doesn’t seem to predict alcohol use all that well. Results don’t support the hypothesis of the relationship between age and high_use, but other hypothesis are supported.

Now, let’s calcuate the predicted probabilites for “high_use”, add those predicted probabilites to the dataset, and use them to make a prediction. Here are cross tabulation of the correct predictions and a nice plot of them:

##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   259    9
##    TRUE     84   30

Defining a loss function to compute the average number of wrong predictions:

## [1] 0.2434555

From all of the 382 subjects, 268 were truly not high users of alcohol, an our model correclty identified 259 of them (97%) as non-high-users. Seems pretty good. However, 114 of these subjects were truly high users of alcohol, and our model identified only 30 one of them (26%). Not so great! We can calculate the average number of wrongly classified cases by hand from the 2x2-table ((9+84)/382 = 0.24), and we can see that that is the same number that the loss function produces. So 24% of the predictions went wrong, and most of those were false negatives. Let’s see if we could get better results by guessing. Let’s compute the averige number of wrong predictions with a probability of 0:

## [1] 0.2984293

We get 29% of average wrong classifications. With a probability of 0, everybody will be dumped in the “FALSE” category. Most of the predictions are still correct, because there are so much more of those non-high-users.

Let’s compute the averige number of wrong predictions with a probability of 1:

## [1] 0.7015707

70% of the classifications are wrong, because now everybody’s in the “TRUE”-category! Seems like our model indeed predicts the alcholol use better than by guessing (although not hugely so).

Then let’s do the cross-validation and calculate the average number of wrong predictions in cross-validation:

## [1] 0.2565445

The prediction error seems to stay between 0.24-0.26, so it seems to be pretty much the same as the model in datacamp.

Because we have extracted from each variable its mean, the lowest values for each variable are now negative and highest values are lower than before. Also the ranges have gotten more narrow. When looking at the scaled values we are really looking at the fluctuations around variable means, in number of standard deviations.

Let’s create a categorical variable “crime” by breaking it into it’s quantiles. We’ll include it into the scaled dataset and drop the old crime variable off.

##      low  med_low med_high     high 
##      127      126      126      127

Then, we’ll divide the dataset into training and testing sets. Let’s choose randomly 80% of the rows in the boston_scaled dataset. Training dataset will include only those 80% of the rows, and the test set will include the rest of the data.

The output produced inludes bunch of information, like coefficients and group means, but it doesn’t really tell us anything about how well the analysis worked (did it predict categories correctly.)

Let’s draw a plot of it:

Let’s save the crimecategories from the testset and then remove crime from the test dataset. Then let’s predict the classes with the test data and produce crosstabulation of the results:

##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       15       8        1    0
##   med_low    5      14       12    0
##   med_high   0       2       18    1
##   high       0       0        0   26

All of those in the highest crime quantile were predicted correctly, so our model separates between high crime areas and other areas really well! Model has a little trouble with predicting the med_high and med_low categories. 18 of 21 of those truly in the med_high category are predicted as so. There’s even more problems with the med_low category: only 14 of those 36 are classified correctly. Low_med group isn’t any better. Looks like the separation works great if we want separate the high crime areas; for other quintiles, there is a lot of overlapping.

Reloading the Boston-dataset and scaling it. Let’s then use eucledian distance to calculate the distances.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4625  4.8241  4.9111  6.1863 14.3970

Let’s perform kmeans clustering with 4 centers and draw a plot of the clusters we obtain:

There seems to be quite a lot of overlapping between the clusters. The problem here is that we don’t yet know what is the optimal number of clusters. We should find the solution were the variation within the clusters is as small as possible. So let’s calculate the total within cluster sum of squares for different number of clusters and visualize the results:

Here we can see a clear change of direction in the graph around 2. We can see that the total within cluster sum of squares decreases somewhat radically till 2 clusters, but after that, changes in variation are less clear. Let’s choose 2 as the number of centers.

Okay, that is probably a slight improvement to the previous, but I still wouldn’t call it perfect.

The data inlcudes 8 variables, which relate to human development index and gender inequality index. Some variables, like GNI, Maternal mortality and Adolescent birth rate are strongly skewed on the left, meanining that there are much more countries which attain very low values on these variables, and very few with high values. The distribution of the number of female representatives, expected education and education ratio seem somewhat normally distributed with most countries gaining values from the middle, and then there are two variables which are slightly skewed on the right, life expectancy at birth and labour ratio between females and males, where most countries seem to attain high values.

Many of the variables correlate highly with each other. We can see, for example, that education ratio correlates positively with life expectancy, expected education and GNI, and negatively with maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate. Life expectancy correlates negatively with maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate (not exactly surprising), and has strong postitive correlation with GNI and expected education.

Then it’s time to perform some principal component analysis and draw a biplot of it.

This doesn’t look super nice. The problem here is that PCA tries to explain the variance in the data the best it can. Since the range for GNI is far larger than for the other variables, PCA will select to project almost entirely in the direction of GNI.

Let’s see then what happens when we standardize the dataset and run the analysis again.

When looking at the arrows we can see that they seem to be going to three directions. Arrows of variables like expected life, expected education and education ratio are horizontal and point straight to left: and we can see, that on the left side of the figure there are countries like Norway and Australia, which surely gain high points on these kind of measures. Arrows of maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate point straight to the other direction, indicating on strong negative correlation with life expectancy and those other variables, which we already new from the correlation plots and can conlcude by common sense. On the very left on the figure, we see some of the poorer countries, like Sierra Leone and Niger.

All of these variable arrows are in line with the x-axis, indicating that these are the variables which by the first principal component separates countries. This makes sense: it does seem like charasteristics related to well-being and not-that-well-being separate between countries well.

The second principal component correlates strongly with gender equality related variabales. Countries which locate up in the figure gain high values on equality measures, and countries which locate down in the figure have lower values on the equality measures. We can see up in the figure Rwanda Iceland, Norway and Finland. Down in the figure we can see countries like Iran and Yemen.

Looks better! Lets start by a little graphical display. Let’s try and plot the weights for all the rats, differentiating between the three groups.

First of all, we can see that almost all the rats gain weight during the study. We can also see that those rats with a higher baseline weight will weight more throughout the study. And third, we can see there are clear differences between the three groups. Those in the group 1 have significantly lower weights throughout the study than those in groups 2 and 3.

Let’s continue our investigations by standardizing the variable Weight and drawing the plot again with the standardized values.

From the standardized plot we can see even more clearly, that those who start off with higher values will attain higher values in all phases of the study. The phenomena is called tracking.

Wouldn’t it be more interesting to observe summary measures of the observations rather than indivdually each of them? Let’s produce a plot of the group means and look at them.

From this plot of the average values we can see that indeed group 1 is clearly separated from the two other groups. Rats in group 1 gain substaintally lower values. Group 2 also attains on average higher values than group 3, although the difference isn’t as big.

Now it’s time to check out wheter we have some outliers messing our game.

Okay, here we have a boxplot displaying mean values for the three groups. We have a few observations that could be considered as outliers. In group two, there seems to be a variable that gains a mean of almost 600mg. Maybe we should filter that one out?

Okay, looks like the removing of the outlier was indeed succesfull!

Let’s then perform some analysis of variance to make sure to look at the differences between the groups.

##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)

Alright, there definetely is some significant difference between these groups! Let’s now include the baseline weight into the analysis as a covariate and check out the results again. This is done because the baseline measure is often correlated with the summary measure.

While the baseline weight is strongly related to the mean weight, there is no evidence of a group diffence. We can conclude that differences in the baseline weights explain all the differences in variance between the three groups.
